o	For reroutes, experts must include a summary of actions taken and HP documentations/KBAs shared to avoid repetition by HP experts. 

5. Offline Routing of Cases:
•	When a customer requests or asks to check the issue over a connection/screen share, callback, a Teams or Zoom meeting invite, screen sharing for troubleshooting, or remote access to their computer, ask the customer to elaborate their issue and assure them that you'll do your best to assist. If the customer insists on another form of communication, inform them that you'll reroute them to HP for further assistance and proceed to do so immediately. Do not attempt to resolve these cases independently.

•	 No Direct Meetings or Call Requests with Customers: Under no circumstances are you to initiate or accept direct meetings or call requests with customers outside of the platform's established communication channels. All communication must remain documented within the ticket system. If the customer requests to check the issue over a connection / screenshare, callback, or a team or zoom meeting or remote access to their computer, inform them that you are rerouting the case back to HP for further assistance.  

•	If a customer says they’re going to create a new ticket or contact HP, inform them that there’s no need to do so, as you will reroute them to HP and proceed to do so immediately.

•	No Instructing Customers to Raise New Tickets: You must not ask customers to close their current ticket and open a new one for any reason. Your responsibility is to resolve the issue within the existing ticket or route it appropriately if necessary.    

•	The ONLY time experts can encourage someone to open a new ticket is if a brand new, unrelated issues is raised by the customer  
•	If the ticket is a follow-up or a customer asks to assign it to a specific support engineer, reroute the ticket to HP using the reroute option immediately.
•	If you are unable to assist the customer, run out of ideas, or realize only HP can fix the issue, please properly inform the customer of the reroute and reroute the ticket to HP using the reroute option immediately.

•	Offline Rerouting Process Violations:
•	Attempting unnecessary troubleshooting steps when offline rerouting is required or mentioned in the guidelines.
•	Delaying rerouting and Rerouting without informing the customer.
•	Not providing helpful resources (Kbs etc) before offline rerouting.  

